"A generation protested" in Ethiopia, Long an ally of the US
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators calling for political changes in Ethiopia came amid violent government resistance.
Witnesses say tens of protesters were killed in gunfire during clashes with police.
Has Ethiopia just collapsed?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable countries, a solid ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country, expanding into more and more areas.
Last week, thousands of people stormed the streets and demanded fundamental political changes.
The government's response was relentless, according to human rights organizations.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Videos circulating about the protests, presumably from last year or early this year, show security people beating young people with sticks, while they have been forced to take a stand against a wall.
The head of the UN Human Rights Authority is now calling for an in-depth investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together and in the future it will become even more difficult," said Rashid Abdi, the project manager of Horn of Africa of the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is Africa's most populous country after Nigeria and its stability is valued by the West.
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terror threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia; few countries in Africa, if any, receive so much Western aid.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a considerable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved drastically - there is a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
The streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
Even though Ethiopia was far from a model of democracy - human rights organizations have continually led government repression - opposition in the country has been curtailed, with dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were sent to exile or prison, killed or driven into the desert's expanses.
But that could change.
"If you suppress people and have these no other options except to protest, it breaks out," said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
The whole youth is protesting.
A generation is protesting.
There are numerous complaints covering everything from land use to stranglehold in terms of power of the ruling coalition.
After a widely criticised election last year, the ruling party and its allies were given the opposition's last seat and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; a battle over this zacky, controversial line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts worry that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, could exploit turmoil and re-arm themselves.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness now explode beneath the surface after years of warping.
The first seems harmless: Smartphones.
It was only in recent years that very many Ethiopians were able to communicate via social media, as cheaper smartphones became increasingly common and Internet services improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does at regular intervals, especially during protests, many people can still communicate via internet proxies that hide where they are staying.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered for protests.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas, the two largest ethnicities in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
Since Eons, the Amharas, who come from Athopia's predominantly Christian highlands, have prospered in politics and economics while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslims and live in flat-land areas.
But that, too, is just changing.
"We are in the process of coordinating under one umbrella," said Mulatu Gemechu, a leader of the Oromos.
The biggest protests took place in areas of the Amhara and Oromos.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, who make up around 6 percent of the population and who are dominant in the military, intelligence agencies, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death from an unpublicized illness in 2012.
He was seen as a tactical genius, a man who could think around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly versed in perceiving early signs of discontent and using special envoys to process opponents and make them harmless.
"The current regime lacks this basic skill," said Mr. Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was selected for relatively opaque reasons to take the position of Mr Meles.
Unlike Mr. Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr. Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the confidence of the security services controlled by the Tigray.
Many fear the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such a stir was in 2005, after thousands protested against elections that, according to analysts, were seemingly pocketed by the government and subsequently stolen.
During the ensuing raids, many protesters were killed, even though there were fewer than in recent months and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
